
[1]indispose

   INDISPO'SE, v.t. s as z.

   1. To disincline; to alienate the mind and render it averse or
   unfavorable to any thing. A love of pleasure indisposes the mind to
   severe study and steady attention to business. The pride and
   selfishness of men indispose them to religious duties.

   2. To render unfit; to disqualify for its proper functions; to
   disorder; as the distemperature of indisposed organs.

   3. To disorder slightly, as the healthy functions of the body.

   It made him rather indisposed than sick.

   4. To make unfavorable or disinclined; with towards.

   The king was sufficiently indisposed towards the persons, or the
   principles of Calvin's disciples.
